{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"50fb0711-5453-4b77-a5b6-5c61cfd5ab71","content":"Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()`. It validates the type and gives a clear assertion message instead of an `InvalidCastException`:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()\n{\n    var factory = new HandlerFactory();\n    var result = factory.Create(\"email\");\n\n    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);\n    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", handler.Type);\n}\n```\n\n**Why it's better:**\n- Fails with a descriptive message (e.g., \"Expected type: EmailHandler. Actual type: SmsHandler\") instead of a raw `InvalidCastException`\n- Implicitly checks for null (null is never an instance of any type)\n- Separates the \"is it the right type?\" concern from the property assertions\n\nThe cast afterward is safe since the assertion already guarantees the type.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"afffe7a5-1822-4c85-8bd4-402d85005b7d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a better MSTest assertion for checking the returned type instead of hard casting. This is about MSTest-specific assertion guidance.\n\nThe answer is `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()` which was introduced in MSTest v2 and returns the cast object. In MSTest v3+, there's `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>(object actual, out T instance)` — actually, let me think about this more carefully.\n\nIn MSTest v2, `Assert.IsInstanceOfType(object value, Type expectedType)` exists but doesn't return the typed value.\n\nIn MSTest v3, `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>(object value)` was added as a generic version, but it still returns void.\n\n\nLet me reconsider what's actually available across versions. The non-generic `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` with a Type parameter has been around since v2, and the generic `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>` variant also exists but returns void. I'm trying to pin down whether any version actually returns the cast instance for direct use. So `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()` returns void, but it handles both the type check and implicitly validates that the value isn't null since null can't be an instance of any type. After the assertion passes, I can safely cast to get the typed reference for additional assertions, which is cleaner than doing a manual cast upfront and checking for null separately.","outputTokens":985,"requestId":"57CB:1BCD7:2E96968:316B210:6A049470"},"id":"811c3951-411a-4dcd-97b5-c4c0bdb83471","timestamp":"2026-05-13T15:11:00.029Z","parentId":"e6ca7946-da92-4e38-96e7-6cf22758164a"}
